{"id":"1903.03456","submitter":"Ming-Cheng Tsai","authors":"Chi-Kwong Li, Ming-Cheng Tsai, Ya-Shu Wang and Ngai-Ching Wong","title":"Nonsurjective maps between rectangular matrix spaces preserving\n  disjointness, triple products, or norms","comments":"This paper will appear in JOT","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.RA math.OA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $M_{m,n}$ be the space of $m\\times n$ real or complex rectangular\nmatrices. Two matrices $A, B \\in M_{m,n}$ are disjoint if $A^*B = 0_n$ and\n$AB^* = 0_m$. In this paper, a characterization is given for linear maps $\\Phi:\nM_{m,n} \\rightarrow M_{r,s}$ sending disjoint matrix pairs to disjoint matrix\npairs, i.e., $A, B \\in M_{m,n}$ are disjoint ensures that $\\Phi(A), \\Phi(B) \\in\nM_{r,s}$ are disjoint. More precisely, it is shown that $\\Phi$ preserves\ndisjointness if and only if $\\Phi$ is of the form $$\\Phi(A) = U\\begin{pmatrix}\nA \\otimes Q_1 & 0 & 0 \\cr 0 & A^t \\otimes Q_2 & 0 \\cr 0 & 0 & 0\n\\cr\\end{pmatrix}V$$ for some unitary matrices $U \\in M_{r,r}$ and $V\\in\nM_{s,s}$, and positive diagonal matrices $Q_1, Q_2$, where $Q_1$ or $Q_2$ may\nbe vacuous. The result is used to characterize nonsurjective linear maps that\npreserve the $JB^*$-triple product, or just the zero triple product, on\nrectangular matrices, defined by $\\{A,B,C\\} = \\frac{1}{2}(AB^*C+CB^*A)$. The\nresult is also applied to characterize linear maps between rectangular matrix\nspaces of different sizes preserving the Schatten $p$-norms or the Ky Fan\n$k$-norms.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 5 Mar 2019 23:30:10 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 13 Jul 2019 16:49:47 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-07-16"}
